04387nam a22004455i 9781503618145DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222000cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97815036181457 a10.1515/97815036181452doi  a(DE-B1597)582552  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aLIT0041902bisacsh1 aSissa, Giulia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Daily Life of the Greek Gods /cGiulia Sissa, Marcel Detienne. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4c©2000  a1 online resource (312 p.) :b1 illustration, 1 map  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aMestizo Spaces / Espaces Métissés00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMap of the Greek Aegean World -- tGenealogies -- tIntroduction -- tI. Homer as an Anthropologist -- tI. Literature? Or Anthropology? -- t2. The Gods: A Particular Nature, A Particular Society -- t3. Spending the Time -- t4. Gods with a Particular Lifestyle -- t5. Savoring the Sweetness of Life -- t6. Divine Interference -- t7. Scenes of Sovereignty -- t8. The Gods and Their Days -- tPart II. The Gods at the Service of the City -- t9. When the Olympians Donned the Citizen's Costume -- t10. A Polytheistic Garden -- t11. Dealings with the Gods -- t12. The Altars and Territories That Were Home to the Divine Powers -- t13. The Affairs of the Gods and the Affairs of Men -- t14. The Power of Women: Hera, Athena, and Their Followers -- t15. A Phallus for Dionysus -- tNotes -- tTranslator's Note -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aDespite the rousing stories of male heroism in battles, the Trojan War transcended the activities of its human participants. For Homer, it was the gods who conducted and accounted for what happened. In the first part of this book, the authors find in Homer's Iliad material for exploring the everyday life of the Greek gods: what their bodies were made of and how they were nourished, the organization of their society, and the sort of life they led both in Olympus and in the human world. The gods are divided in their human nature: at once a fantasized model of infinite joys and an edifying example of engagement in the world, they have loves, festivities, and quarrels. In the second part, the authors show how citizens carried on everyday relations with the gods and those who would become the Olympians, inviting them to reside with humans organized in cities. At the heart of rituals and of social life, the gods were omnipresent: in sacrifices, at meals, in political assemblies, in war, in sexuality. In brief, the authors show how the gods were indispensable to the everyday social organization of Greek cities. To set on stage a number of gods implicated in the world of human beings, the authors give precedence to the feminine over the masculine, choosing to show how such great powers as Hera and Athena wielded their sovereignty over cities, reigning over not only the activities of women but also the moulding of future citizens. Equally important, the authors turn to Dionysus and follow the evolution of one of his forms, that of the phallus paraded in processions. Under this god, so attentive to all things feminine, the authors explore the typically civic ways of thinking about the relations between natural fecundity and the sexuality of daily life.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh1 aDetienne, Marcel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150361814540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503618145423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503618145/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles